Antiquarians reported recovered [[:en:Bronze mirror|Bronze mirror]]s from the site in 1877 and some stone masonry was removed from the site in 1915, but the current location of these artifacts is now unknown. [[:en:Archaeological excavations|Archaeological excavations]] have been conducted in surveys have been conducted in 1955 and from 1984 to 1986. Despite the poor conditions the site, a number of [[:en:Grave goods|Grave goods]] have been detected inside and outside the sarcophagus, including [[:en:Jadeite|Jadeite]] ''[[magatama]]'' and jadeite, jasper or glass beads, copper and iron swords, spears, axes and other items. From these artifacts and the unusual construction technique and style of ''haniwa'', the tumulus is believed to date from the end of the 4th century. Most of the recovered artifacts are currently stored at [[Kyoto University]], but three elliptical cylindrical ''haniwa'' and two pot-shaped pottery have been designated as Tangible Cultural Properties of Kashiwara City, and are currently stored in the Kashiwara City Historical Museum.<ref name="Bunka2">{{cite web |url=http://www.city.kashiwara.osaka.jp/docs/2014082000061/?doc_id=1454 |title=松岳山古墳出土品|trans-title= Matsuokayama Kofun Artifacts|language=Japanese |publisher=Kashiwara City |accessdate=February 20, 2022}}</ref>
The Matsuokayama Kofun is located about a 14-drive from [[Kawachi-Kokubu Station]] on the [[Kintetsu Osaka Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
;Total length: between 130 and 155 meters ;Anterior rectangular portion: 32 meters wide x 6 meters high, 2-tier ;Posterior circular portion: 72 meter diameter 16 meters high, 3-tiers or 4-tiers
